(578, 17, 'What will this state pattern polymorphism output? interface State { void handle(); } } } } Context context = new Context(); context.setState(new ConcreteStateA()); context.request();', 'class Context {\nprivate State state;\npublic void setState(State state) { this.state = state; }\npublic void request() { state.handle(); }\nclass ConcreteStateA implements State {\npublic void handle() { System.out.println(\"Handling in State A\"); }\nclass ConcreteStateB implements State {\npublic void handle() { System.out.println(\"Handling in State B\"); }', 'Handling in State B', 'Handling in State A', 'Nothing', 'B', 'Intermediate', 'Simulation question'),
(579, 17, 'What happens with this chain of responsibility polymorphism? abstract class Handler { } if (request.equals(\"A\")) { } else if (nextHandler != null) { nextHandler.handleRequest(request); } } } if (request.equals(\"B\")) { } } } Handler h1 = new ConcreteHandlerA(); Handler h2 = new ConcreteHandlerB(); h1.setNext(h2); h1.handleRequest(\"B\");', 'protected Handler nextHandler;\npublic void setNext(Handler handler) { this.nextHandler = handler; }\npublic abstract void handleRequest(String request);\nclass ConcreteHandlerA extends Handler {\npublic void handleRequest(String request) {\nSystem.out.println(\"Handler A processing\");\nclass ConcreteHandlerB extends Handler {\npublic void handleRequest(String request) {\nSystem.out.println(\"Handler B processing\");', 'Handler A processing', 'Handler B processing', 'Nothing', 'B', 'Intermediate', 'Simulation question'),
(580, 17, 'What is the output of this bridge pattern polymorphism? interface DrawingAPI { void drawCircle(int x, int y, int radius); } } } abstract class Shape { } Circle(int x, int y, int radius, DrawingAPI drawingAPI) { super(drawingAPI); this.x = x; this.y = y; this.radius = radius; } } circle.draw();', 'class DrawingAPI1 implements DrawingAPI {\npublic void drawCircle(int x, int y, int radius) {\nSystem.out.println(\"API1 drawing circle\");\nprotected DrawingAPI drawingAPI;\nShape(DrawingAPI drawingAPI) { this.drawingAPI = drawingAPI; }\npublic abstract void draw();\nclass Circle extends Shape {\nprivate int x, y, radius;\npublic void draw() { drawingAPI.drawCircle(x, y, radius); }\nShape circle = new Circle(1, 2, 3, new DrawingAPI1());', 'Drawing circle', 'API1 drawing circle', 'Compilation error', 'B', 'Intermediate', 'Simulation question'),
(581, 14, ' Which code correctly declares a class in Java? How do you create an object of class Student? What is the default value of a String field in a class if it is not initialized? Given this code: String title; } Book b = new Book(); What is the output? Which keyword is used to create an object in Java? Which of the following correctly defines a constructor? Which code assigns a value to an object\'s field? String name; } Dog d = new Dog(); What will be the output? String brand = \"Dell\"; } Laptop l = new Laptop(); Which is true about a constructor? Given this code: String brand; int year; Car(String b, int y) { brand = b; year = y; } } Car c = new Car(\"Toyota\", 2020); What is the brand of the car? Which keyword refers to the current object inside a class? What is the output of this code? String name; Student(String n) { name = n; } } Student s = new Student(\"Anna\"); Which code creates two different objects of class Person? What will happen if a class has no constructor defined? Which of the following is correct about instance variables in a class?', 'class Student {}\nclass Book {\nSystem.out.println(b.title);\nclass Dog {\nclass Laptop {\nSystem.out.println(l.brand);\nclass Car {\nclass Student {\nSystem.out.println(s.name);\nclass Person {}', 'They are declared inside methods', 'They belong to objects of the class', 'They must always be static', 'B', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(582, 14, 'In Java, which keyword is used to create a class? d. void', '', 'object', 'class', 'new', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(583, 14, 'What will be the correct way to create an object of a class named Student? d. obj Student = new Student;', '', 'Student = new Student();', 'Student obj = Student();', 'Student obj = new Student();', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(584, 14, 'Consider this code: String title; } Which statement correctly creates a Book object? d. Book -> new;', 'class Book {', 'Book.title = \"Java\";', 'Book b = new Book();', 'new Book = b;', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(585, 14, 'A class is often referred to as: d. A function', '', 'An object’s instance', 'A blueprint for objects', 'A memory location', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(586, 14, 'If Car is a class, then Car myCar = new Car(); means: d. Importing the Car library', '', 'Declaring a variable only', 'Creating a new class', 'Instantiating an object of class Car', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(587, 14, 'What is the default access modifier of class members in Java if not specified? d. package-private (default) ✅ Answer: d. package-private (default)', '', 'public', 'private', 'protected', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(588, 14, 'Given the class: String name; int age; } How do you assign a value \"Juan\" to name in a Person object named p1? d. setName(p1,\"Juan\");', 'class Person {', 'p1.name = \"Juan\";', 'name.p1 = \"Juan\";', 'p1(\"Juan\");', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(589, 14, 'Which of the following is NOT true about objects? d. Objects can access class attributes', '', 'Objects consume memory when created', 'Objects are instances of a class', 'Objects can exist without a class', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(590, 14, 'Suppose you created a class: double radius; } Which is the correct way to create two different Circle objects? d. Circle c1 = new Circle; Circle c2 = new Circle;', 'class Circle {', 'Circle c1 = new Circle(); Circle c2 = new Circle();', 'Circle c1, c2 = new Circle();', 'Circle c1 = Circle(); Circle c2 = Circle();', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(591, 14, 'If no constructor is defined in a class, what happens? d. Only static methods can be used', '', 'The program won’t run', 'Java automatically provides a default constructor', 'The class becomes abstract', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(592, 14, 'Which of the following best defines an object in OOP? d. A reserved keyword in Java', '', 'A copy of a constructor', 'A function within a class', 'An instance of a class containing data and behavior', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(593, 14, 'Consider: int id; String name; } Which code creates an object and assigns values? d. Student obj = Student(1,\"Liza\");', 'class Student {', 'Student s; s.id=1; s.name=\"Liza\";', 'Student s = new Student(); s.id=1; s.name=\"Liza\";', 'Student = new Student(); id=1; name=\"Liza\";', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(594, 14, 'What is the relationship between a class and an object? d. Class is memory; object is CPU instruction', '', 'Class is a variable; object is a function', 'Class defines structure; object is an instance of it', 'Class is temporary; object is permanent', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(595, 14, 'Which of these statements about methods inside a class is correct? d. Methods are constructors', '', 'Methods cannot access attributes', 'Methods define behaviors of objects', 'Methods are always static', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(596, 14, 'Why do we use classes in Java? d. To replace functions entirely', '', 'To reduce code readability', 'To allow only one object to exist', 'To group related data (attributes) and methods (behaviors)', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(597, 14, 'In Java, what happens if you do not explicitly define any constructor in a class? d. The class becomes abstract', '', 'The program will not compile', 'Java provides a default constructor automatically', 'An error occurs at runtime', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(598, 14, 'Which of the following best describes constructor overloading? d. A constructor that calls another class', '', 'Constructors with the same name but different parameter lists', 'Constructors with the same name and same parameters', 'Multiple constructors in different classes', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(599, 14, 'What does the keyword this refer to inside a class? d. The main method', '', 'The superclass', 'The current object', 'A static variable', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(600, 14, 'Which of the following about static variables is true? d. Static variables must be declared final', '', 'Each object has its own copy of a static variable', 'Static variables belong to the class, not to objects', 'Static variables cannot be accessed in static methods', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(601, 14, 'Consider this code: static int count = 0; Student() { count++; } } If 5 objects of Student are created, what will be the value of count? d. undefined', 'class Student {', '0', '1', '5', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(602, 14, 'Which of these is a correct way to call one constructor from another in the same class? d. init()', '', 'constructor()', 'this()', 'super()', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(603, 14, 'An array of objects in Java is: d. Not allowed in Java', '', 'A collection of primitive values', 'A set of object references stored in contiguous memory', 'A group of static methods', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(604, 14, 'Which statement is true about a parameterized constructor? d. It returns a value', '', 'It must always be public', 'It allows object initialization with specific values', 'It cannot coexist with a default constructor', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(605, 14, 'What does composition in OOP mean? d. A class overloads its methods', '', 'A class inherits from another class', 'A class contains another class as a field', 'A class calls its parent constructor', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(606, 14, 'What is the purpose of a copy constructor? d. To copy methods only', '', 'To duplicate the code of a class', 'To copy the attributes of one object into another', 'To overload methods', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(607, 14, 'Which of the following is NOT true about constructors in Java? d. They can be declared static ✅ Answer: d. They can be declared static', '', 'They have the same name as the class', 'They do not return a value', 'They can be overloaded', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(608, 14, 'If a method is declared as static, how should it be called? d. Using the super keyword', '', 'Only through an object', 'Only through the this keyword', 'Using the class name', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(609, 14, 'What is the correct order of execution when an object is created? d. Object is created → Class is loaded → Constructor is executed', '', 'Class is loaded → Constructor is executed → Object is created', 'Constructor is executed → Class is loaded → Object is created', 'Class is loaded → Object is created → Constructor is executed', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(610, 14, 'Which is an example of method overloading? d. Two methods in a subclass with the same name', '', 'Two methods with the same name but different parameter lists', 'Two methods with the same name and same parameter lists', 'Two methods in different classes with the same name', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(611, 14, 'Given: double radius; Circle(double r) { radius = r; } double area() { return Math.PI * radius * radius; } } What will new Circle(3).area(); return? d. Compilation error', 'class Circle {', '9', '6.28', '28.27 (approx)', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(612, 15, 'What does encapsulation mean in OOP? d. Making all variables global', '', 'Wrapping data and methods into one unit', 'Hiding classes inside other classes', 'Using only public attributes', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(613, 15, 'Which access modifier is used to implement data hiding in encapsulation? d. final', '', 'public', 'private', 'static', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(614, 15, 'Why do we use encapsulation? d. To automatically create constructors', '', 'To increase speed of execution', 'To hide data and restrict direct access', 'To allow all classes to access variables', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(615, 15, 'Which of the following is NOT a benefit of encapsulation? d. Faster compilation ✅ Answer: d. Faster compilation', '', 'Better control of data', 'Improved security', 'Ability to change implementation without affecting users', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(616, 15, 'How can private fields of a class be accessed outside that class? d. Directly using object reference', '', 'Using getter and setter methods', 'By importing the private variable', 'By declaring it static', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(617, 15, 'What is the correct form of a getter method in Java? d. static int getValue()', '', 'public void getValue()', 'private String getName()', 'public String getName()', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(618, 15, 'What is the correct form of a setter method in Java? d. void setValue()', '', 'public void setValue(int v) { this.value = v; }', 'private void setValue(int v)', 'public setValue(int v)', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(619, 15, 'In encapsulation, fields of a class are usually declared as: d. protected', '', 'public', 'static', 'private', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(620, 15, 'Which of the following best describes data hiding? d. Making data final', '', 'Preventing access to a variable by making it private', 'Deleting unused data', 'Storing variables in an array', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(621, 15, 'If a field is declared private, what will happen when we try to access it directly from outside the class? d. No error', '', 'Runtime error', 'Compile-time error', 'Logical error', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(622, 15, 'Which of the following demonstrates encapsulation correctly? d. Using constructors without methods', '', 'Public variables and private methods', 'Private variables with public getters and setters', 'Static variables only', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(623, 15, 'Encapsulation improves data integrity by: d. Hiding constructors', '', 'Allowing uncontrolled modification of fields', 'Preventing invalid data using setter validation', 'Making all methods private', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(624, 15, 'Which of the following keywords is not directly related to encapsulation? d. extends ✅ Answer: d. extends', '', 'private', 'public', 'getter', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(625, 15, 'In Java, what convention is used for naming getter methods of a boolean field? d. booleanVariable()', '', 'getVariable()', 'setVariable()', 'isVariable()', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(626, 15, 'Encapsulation allows: d. Methods to become static by default', '', 'Separation of class implementation from class use', 'Objects to directly manipulate each other’s fields', 'Elimination of constructors', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(627, 15, 'Which of the following is a common way to validate data in encapsulation? d. By making the field static', '', 'Inside the getter', 'Inside the setter', 'Inside the constructor only', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(628, 15, 'What is the main advantage of making a class immutable? d. It avoids creating getters', '', 'Its fields can be modified anytime', 'Objects cannot be changed once created, ensuring safety', 'It uses less memory', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(629, 15, 'Which of the following is required to make a class immutable? d. Avoid constructors', '', 'Make the class abstract', 'Declare fields private and final, no setters', 'Use only static variables', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(630, 15, 'If a setter method restricts assigning negative values to age, this is an example of: d. Polymorphism', '', 'Data hiding', 'Validation inside encapsulation', 'Constructor chaining', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(631, 15, 'Which is true when using constructor-based encapsulation? d. Getters are unnecessary', '', 'Fields can only be initialized when the object is created', 'Fields must be declared public', 'Constructors replace encapsulation', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question');
REPLACE INTO `questions` (`id`, `topic_id`, `question_text`, `code_snippet`, `option_a`, `option_b`, `option_c`, `correct_option`, `class_level`, `question_type`) VALUES
(632, 15, 'In an immutable class, how do we allow access to private fields? d. By declaring them static', '', 'Using public setters', 'Using public getters only', 'By making them public', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(633, 15, 'Which access modifier combination demonstrates proper encapsulation? d. Final fields with public setters', '', 'Private fields, public getters/setters', 'Public fields, private getters', 'Protected fields, static methods', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(634, 15, 'Which of the following violates encapsulation? d. A final private field with no setter', '', 'A private field with a setter that validates input', 'A private field with only a getter', 'A public field with no methods', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(635, 15, 'Why is it considered bad practice to always create setters for all fields? d. Setters cannot be compiled', '', 'Setters make the class immutable', 'Setters may allow uncontrolled modification of sensitive fields', 'Setters make constructors unusable', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(636, 15, 'Which of the following makes a partially encapsulated class? d. All fields are private with only setters', '', 'Some fields have both getters and setters, while others only have getters', 'All fields are public', 'All fields are private without methods', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(637, 15, 'Consider: Student(int id, String name) { this.id = id; this.name = name; } } What principle is shown here? d. Dynamic binding', 'class Student {\nprivate String name;\nprivate final int id;\npublic String getName() { return name; }\npublic int getId() { return id; }', 'Encapsulation with immutability of id', 'Polymorphism', 'Inheritance', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(638, 15, 'What is the disadvantage of exposing setters for all fields? d. It makes getters useless', '', 'It increases compilation time', 'It reduces data integrity', 'It prevents constructors from working', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(639, 15, 'Which statement is true about read-only encapsulation? d. Fields are final and public', '', 'Fields are private with setters only', 'Fields are private with getters only', 'Fields are public with no methods', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(640, 15, 'If you want to restrict an attribute to be set only once at object creation, you should: d. Use a static field', '', 'Use a setter', 'Use a public variable', 'Use a private final variable with constructor assignment', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(641, 15, 'Which is an example of best practice in encapsulation? d. Remove all constructors to enforce immutability', '', 'Make all fields public for easier access', 'Provide setters for sensitive data like passwords', 'Validate input inside setter methods before updating fields', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(642, 16, 'In OOP, inheritance allows: d. Declaring multiple main methods', '', 'Creating multiple constructors', 'A class to use properties and methods of another class', 'Direct access to private fields of another class', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(643, 16, 'The class that is inherited from is called: d. Object class', '', 'Subclass', 'Parent class (or Superclass)', 'Interface', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(644, 16, 'The class that inherits another class is called: d. Constructor class', '', 'Parent class', 'Superclass', 'Subclass (or Child class)', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(645, 16, 'Which keyword is used in Java to inherit a class? d. implements', '', 'import', 'extends', 'inherit', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(646, 16, 'Which of the following is the correct example of inheritance in Java? Here, Dog is: d. Abstract class', 'class Animal { }\nclass Dog extends Animal { }', 'Parent class', 'Subclass', 'Interface', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(647, 16, 'What is the main benefit of inheritance? d. Prevents object creation', '', 'Reduces memory usage', 'Code reusability', 'Faster compilation', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(648, 16, 'In Java, a class can directly inherit from: d. Only abstract classes', '', 'Only one superclass', 'Multiple superclasses', 'Both a class and an interface', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(649, 16, 'What is the relationship between Car (child) and Vehicle (parent) in: d. Car has-a Vehicle', 'class Vehicle { }\nclass Car extends Vehicle { }', 'Vehicle is-a Car', 'Car is-a Vehicle', 'Vehicle has-a Car', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(650, 16, 'Which class in Java is the ultimate superclass of all classes? d. Super', '', 'Main', 'Object', 'Class', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(651, 16, 'If class A extends class B, then which is true? d. A and B are unrelated', '', 'A is the parent of B', 'B is the child of A', 'A is the child of B', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(652, 16, 'Which of the following is not inherited by a subclass? d. Constructors', '', 'Public methods', 'Private fields', 'Protected methods', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(653, 16, 'Consider: String name; } int id; } Which field(s) does Student have? d. None', 'class Person {\nclass Student extends Person {', 'Only id', 'Only name', 'Both name and id', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(654, 16, 'Which keyword is used to call the parent class constructor? d. extends()', '', 'this()', 'super()', 'parent()', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(655, 16, 'Which type of inheritance is not supported in Java classes? d. Multiple (with classes) ✅ Answer: d. Multiple (with classes)', '', 'Single', 'Multilevel', 'Hierarchical', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(656, 16, 'What is printed? void sound() { System.out.println(\"Animal makes sound\"); } } void bark() { System.out.println(\"Dog barks\"); } } Dog d = new Dog(); d.sound(); d.bark(); } } Dog barks d. Nothing', 'class Animal {\nclass Dog extends Animal {\npublic class Test {\npublic static void main(String[] args) {', 'Compilation error', 'Animal makes sound', 'Dog barks only', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(657, 16, 'Which of the following demonstrates method overriding? d. Same method name, different return type in the same class', '', 'Same method name, different parameters in the same class', 'Same method name, same parameters in parent and child classes', 'Two unrelated classes with the same method name', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(658, 16, 'What is the purpose of the super keyword? d. To declare static fields', '', 'To call a method in the current class', 'To create a subclass', 'To call the parent class constructor or method', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(659, 16, 'Which type of inheritance is shown here? d. Hierarchical', 'class A { }\nclass B extends A { }\nclass C extends B { }', 'Single', 'Multiple', 'Multilevel', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(660, 16, 'Which of the following inheritance types is demonstrated here? d. Hybrid', 'class Vehicle { }\nclass Car extends Vehicle { }\nclass Bike extends Vehicle { }', 'Multilevel', 'Hierarchical', 'Multiple', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(661, 16, 'Which method cannot be overridden in Java? d. Protected methods', '', 'Final methods', 'Abstract methods', 'Public methods', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(662, 16, 'Which statement is true about constructors in inheritance? d. Constructors must always be private', '', 'Constructors are inherited', 'Constructors are not inherited but can be called using super()', 'Subclass does not need constructors', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(663, 16, 'What will the following program output? A() { System.out.println(\"A\'s Constructor\"); } } B() { System.out.println(\"B\'s Constructor\"); } } B obj = new B(); } } B’s Constructor d. Compilation error A\'s Constructor B\'s Constructor', 'class A {\nclass B extends A {\npublic class Test {\npublic static void main(String[] args) {', 'A’s Constructor', 'B’s Constructor', 'A’s Constructor', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(664, 16, 'Which access modifier allows a field/method to be inherited only by subclasses (even in different packages)? d. public', '', 'private', 'default', 'protected', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(665, 16, 'Which rule applies when overriding a method? d. Access modifier must be stricter', '', 'Return type must always be different', 'Parameter list must be the same', 'Method name can change', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(666, 16, 'If a method in the parent class is declared private, then: d. It automatically becomes protected', '', 'It is inherited and can be overridden', 'It is inherited but cannot be overridden', 'It is not inherited by the subclass', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(667, 16, 'What will happen if both parent and child have the same method signature? d. Both methods execute', '', 'Compiler error', 'The child’s method overrides the parent’s method', 'The parent’s method is always executed', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(668, 16, 'Which of the following is true about Java inheritance? d. A superclass cannot have a constructor', '', 'Java supports multiple inheritance with classes', 'A subclass can extend more than one superclass', 'Java prevents multiple inheritance to avoid ambiguity', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(669, 16, 'Which keyword is used when a subclass wants to call its own constructor first, then the parent’s constructor? d. extends()', '', 'super() inside the first line of the constructor', 'this() followed by super()', 'parent()', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(670, 16, 'What will be printed? void sound() { System.out.println(\"Animal sound\"); } } @Override void sound() { System.out.println(\"Dog barks\"); } } } } d. Both', 'class Animal {\nclass Dog extends Animal {\npublic class Test {\npublic static void main(String[] args) {\nAnimal a = new Dog();', 'Animal sound', 'Dog barks', 'Compilation error', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(671, 16, 'Why does Java not allow multiple inheritance with classes? d. Because super() cannot call two constructors', '', 'It increases memory size', 'To avoid complexity and ambiguity (Diamond problem)', 'Because interfaces are better', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(672, 13, 'What does OOP stand for? d. Organized Object Principle', '', 'Object-Oriented Programming', 'Open Operations Process', 'Overloaded Object Protocol', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(673, 13, 'Which of the following is not a feature of OOP? d. Compilation ✅ Answer: d. Compilation', '', 'Inheritance', 'Encapsulation', 'Polymorphism', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(674, 13, 'The main building blocks of OOP are: d. Loops and Conditions', '', 'Methods and Functions', 'Classes and Objects', 'Constructors and Destructors', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(675, 13, 'Which OOP concept means “wrapping data and methods into a single unit”? d. Inheritance', '', 'Abstraction', 'Polymorphism', 'Encapsulation', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(676, 13, 'Which OOP concept allows one class to acquire the properties of another? d. Encapsulation', '', 'Abstraction', 'Inheritance', 'Polymorphism', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(677, 13, 'Which OOP concept allows objects to take many forms (e.g., one method behaves differently)? d. Inheritance', '', 'Polymorphism', 'Encapsulation', 'Abstraction', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(678, 13, 'Which OOP principle is used when only the essential details are shown and unnecessary details are hidden? d. Overloading', '', 'Abstraction', 'Encapsulation', 'Polymorphism', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(679, 13, 'Which of the following best describes an object in OOP? d. A keyword in Java', '', 'A blueprint for creating classes', 'An instance of a class', 'A type of constructor', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(680, 13, 'Which of the following best describes a class? d. A loop structure', '', 'A variable that stores values', 'A blueprint/template for creating objects', 'A method for encapsulation', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(681, 13, 'In OOP, which keyword is used in Java to create an object? d. create', '', 'make', 'new', 'object', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(682, 13, 'What is the main advantage of OOP compared to procedural programming? d. It avoids loops', '', 'Code is faster to execute', 'It focuses on objects, making code reusable and easier to maintain', 'It uses fewer variables', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(683, 13, 'Which of the following is true about OOP? d. OOP does not allow encapsulation', '', 'OOP is based on functions only', 'OOP is based on real-world objects and behaviors', 'OOP cannot use inheritance', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(684, 13, 'Which of the following is an example of encapsulation? d. Hiding constructors', '', 'Declaring all fields as public', 'Declaring fields as private and using getters/setters', 'Using multiple classes without methods', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
