(795, 26, 'Which design pattern is responsible for creating objects without exposing the creation logic? d. Adapter', '', 'Observer', 'Factory', 'Singleton', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(796, 26, 'Which of the following is an example of a creational design pattern? d. Adapter', '', 'Observer', 'Singleton', 'Decorator', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(797, 26, 'Which design pattern ensures that only one instance of a class is created? d. Builder', '', 'Observer', 'Singleton', 'Factory', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(798, 26, 'The Observer pattern is an example of which type of design pattern? d. Architectural', '', 'Creational', 'Structural', 'Behavioral', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(799, 26, 'The Adapter pattern is mainly used to: d. Notify observers of changes', '', 'Create objects step by step', 'Allow incompatible interfaces to work together', 'Ensure only one object is created', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(800, 26, 'Which design pattern is often compared to a real-world plug adapter? d. Factory', '', 'Singleton', 'Observer', 'Adapter', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(801, 26, 'The Decorator pattern is used to: d. Translate one interface into another', '', 'Add new behavior to an object dynamically without altering its structure', 'Replace inheritance', 'Create only one object', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(802, 26, 'Which of the following is true about design patterns? d. They are specific to Java only', '', 'They are finished pieces of code ready to copy-paste', 'They provide templates for solving problems', 'They must be used in every project', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(803, 26, 'Which creational design pattern lets you build a complex object step by step? d. Observer', '', 'Builder', 'Factory', 'Adapter', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(804, 26, 'The Strategy pattern allows: d. Building objects step by step', '', 'Selecting an algorithm’s behavior at runtime', 'Only one instance of a class', 'Adapting incompatible interfaces', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(805, 26, 'Which type of design pattern is the Composite pattern? d. Hybrid', '', 'Creational', 'Structural', 'Behavioral', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(806, 26, 'Why should students learn design patterns early in OOP? d. To make projects longer and harder', '', 'To memorize code syntax', 'To solve recurring software problems more efficiently', 'To replace all programming languages', 'A', 'Beginner', 'Quiz question'),
(807, 26, 'Which design pattern would you use if you want to create only one database connection object in an application? d. Adapter', '', 'Factory', 'Singleton', 'Observer', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(808, 26, 'Given the following Java code: if (instance == null) { instance = new DBConnection(); } return instance; } } Which design pattern is being implemented? d. Strategy', 'class DBConnection {\nprivate static DBConnection instance;\nprivate DBConnection() {}\npublic static DBConnection getInstance() {', 'Factory', 'Singleton', 'Builder', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(809, 26, 'The Factory Method pattern is best used when: d. You want to add behavior at runtime', '', 'You want to ensure only one instance of a class', 'You want to allow subclasses to decide which class to instantiate', 'You want to adapt incompatible interfaces', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(810, 26, 'Consider this code snippet: interface Shape { void draw(); } } } } } if (type.equals(\"CIRCLE\")) return new Circle(); if (type.equals(\"RECTANGLE\")) return new Rectangle(); return null; } } Which design pattern is used here? d. Adapter', 'class Circle implements Shape {\npublic void draw() {\nSystem.out.println(\"Drawing Circle\");\nclass Rectangle implements Shape {\npublic void draw() {\nSystem.out.println(\"Drawing Rectangle\");\nclass ShapeFactory {\npublic Shape getShape(String type) {', 'Singleton', 'Factory', 'Observer', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(811, 26, 'Which design pattern is demonstrated by Java’s java.util.Observer and Observable classes? d. Builder', '', 'Adapter', 'Observer', 'Singleton', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(812, 26, 'Simulation: You are building a notification system where multiple users must be notified when a new message arrives. Which design pattern should you use? d. Decorator', '', 'Factory', 'Adapter', 'Observer', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(813, 26, 'The Strategy Pattern allows: d. Adding behavior dynamically', '', 'Changing the algorithm at runtime without modifying the client code', 'Ensuring only one object is created', 'Translating one interface into another', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(814, 26, 'Code Simulation: interface PaymentStrategy { void pay(int amount); } } } } } Which pattern is being implemented here? d. Factory', 'class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentStrategy {\npublic void pay(int amount) {\nSystem.out.println(\"Paid \" + amount + \" using Credit Card.\");\nclass PaypalPayment implements PaymentStrategy {\npublic void pay(int amount) {\nSystem.out.println(\"Paid \" + amount + \" using PayPal.\");', 'Singleton', 'Strategy', 'Observer', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(815, 26, 'The Decorator pattern is best applied when: d. You want to decide which subclass to instantiate', '', 'You need to dynamically add new responsibilities to objects', 'You want to adapt an old interface to a new one', 'You want to enforce single instance creation', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(816, 26, 'Example simulation: interface Coffee { String getDescription(); double getCost(); } } this.coffee = coffee; } } Which pattern is applied here? d. Observer', 'class SimpleCoffee implements Coffee {\npublic String getDescription() { return \"Simple Coffee\"; }\npublic double getCost() { return 10; }\nclass MilkDecorator implements Coffee {\nprivate Coffee coffee;\npublic MilkDecorator(Coffee coffee) {\npublic String getDescription() { return coffee.getDescription() + \", Milk\"; }\npublic double getCost() { return coffee.getCost() + 2; }', 'Factory', 'Strategy', 'Decorator', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(817, 26, 'The Adapter pattern is useful when: d. You want to notify multiple objects', '', 'You want objects with incompatible interfaces to work together', 'You want only one instance of a class', 'You want to choose an algorithm dynamically', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question'),
(818, 26, 'Example simulation: } } interface NewPrinter { void print(String text); } this.oldPrinter = oldPrinter; } oldPrinter.printOld(text); } } Which design pattern is used here? d. Builder', 'class OldPrinter {\npublic void printOld(String text) {\nSystem.out.println(\"Old Printer: \" + text);\nclass PrinterAdapter implements NewPrinter {\nprivate OldPrinter oldPrinter;\npublic PrinterAdapter(OldPrinter oldPrinter) {\npublic void print(String text) {', 'Observer', 'Adapter', 'Singleton', 'A', 'Intermediate', 'Quiz question');
